===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|frm|en}} {{m|frm|abatement}}, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{m|fro|abatre}}<ref name=CH>{{R:CDOE|page=2}}</ref>. Equivalent to {{suffix|abate|ment|t1=to beat down|t2=the result of|lang=en}}.

====Pronunciation====
* {{audio|en-us-abatement.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}
* {{a|US|UK}} {{IPA|/əˈbeɪt.mənt/|lang=en}}

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# The act of [[abating]], or the state of being [[abate]]d; a [[lessening]], [[diminution]], or reduction; a [[moderation]]; removal or putting an end to; the suppression of. {{defdate|First attested from 1340 to 1470.}}<ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=2}}</ref><ref name=CH/>
#: ''the '''abatement''' of a nuisance is the suppression thereof.''
# The amount abated; that which is taken away by way of reduction; [[deduction]]; [[decrease]]; a [[rebate]] or [[discount]] allowed; in particular from a tax. {{defdate|Late 15<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
# {{lb|en|heraldry}} A mark of [[dishonor]] on an [[escutcheon]]; any [[figure]] added to the [[coat of arms]] tending to lower the [[dignity]] or [[station]] of the [[bearer]].<ref name =WI3/>{{defdate|Early 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>

